terviews with evangelical leaders and teenagers, she examines the strategy to shift from a negative "just say no" approach to a positive one: "just say yes" to great sex within marriage. Making Chastity Sexy sheds new light on an abstinence campaign that has successfully recast a traditionally feminist idea—"my body, my choice"—into a powerful message, but one that Gardner suggests may ultimately reduce evangelicalism’s transformative power. Focusing on the United States, her study also includes a comparative dimension by examining the export of this evangelical agenda to sub-Saharan Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSex instruction for teenagersxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSexual abstinencexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSexual abstinencexStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aTeenagersxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aabstinence campaigns.  aamerican society.  aamerican teens.  achastity movement.  achastity.  achristian education.  aevangelical christians.  aevangelical leaders.  afeminist ideals.  agender and sexuality.  agender politics.  ainterviews.  amarriage and sex.  amodern society.  anonfiction study.  apersuasion.  apledge of abstinence.  arhetorical analysis.  asex and relationships.  asex saturated world.  asex.  asociology.  asub saharan africa.  atheology.  aunited states.  avirginity.  ayoung people.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026728240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095055940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520950559/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Pa